[{"location":"index.html#DCPORBIT.jl:-DisContinuous-Particle-ORBIT","page":"Home","title":"DCPORBIT.jl: DisContinuous Particle ORBIT","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"index.html","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"Solving the equations of motion for charged particles in discontinuous fields.","category":"page"},{"location":"index.html","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"The code has now been slightly extended to give the author a playground to experiment with some numerical implementations. Therefore, some scripts may not work.","category":"page"},{"location":"index.html#Features","page":"Home","title":"Features","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"index.html","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"dcporbit.jl solves the equations of motion of a charged particle in a magnetic field:","category":"page"},{"location":"index.html","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"beginalign \n    mathbfx          = dotmathbfx \n    ddotmathbfx   = dotmathbfxtimes mathbfB(mathbfxt)\nendalign","category":"page"},{"location":"index.html","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"where mathbfB may be discontinuous. Other features include:","category":"page"},{"location":"index.html","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"4th order Runge-Kutta method with event location used for time integration.\nIntegrate groups of particles by initialising them all at once.\nCurrent implementation is only in Cartesian coordinates.\nCan compute analytic solution in very limited cases.","category":"page"},{"location":"index.html","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"This code was originally written for an honors thesis and to assist with implementation of a discontinuous ODE solver implemented in VENUS-LEVIS. Details on the routines and their implementation in VENUS-LEVIS can be found here.","category":"page"},{"location":"index.html#Example-usage","page":"Home","title":"Example usage","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"index.html","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"using dcporbit","category":"page"},{"location":"index.html","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"x₀ = [0.,0.,0.]\nv₀ = [1.,0.,0.]\n\nt_f = 10.0\nΔt = 1.e-3","category":"page"},{"location":"index.html","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"Set up a magnetic field purely in the mathbfz direction and tell the code what the equations of motion are","category":"page"},{"location":"index.html","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"Bfield(x,t) = [0.,0.,1.]\n\nODE = forces(Bfield)","category":"page"},{"location":"index.html","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"Initialise a particle object in full orbit mode (note that mode=GuidingCentre is also possible)","category":"page"},{"location":"index.html","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"mode = FullOrbit\np = particle(x₀,v₀,mode,Δt,Bfield)","category":"page"},{"location":"index.html","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"Solve the particle orbit, this updates the particle object from above,","category":"page"},{"location":"index.html","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"solve_orbit!(p,ODE,t_f,method=:RK4)","category":"page"},{"location":"index.html#Similar-software","page":"Home","title":"Similar software","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"index.html","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"The most relevant code is VENUS-LEVIS, which computes particle orbits in a variety of magnetic field geometries, including discontinuous fields generated by the Stepped Pressure Equilibrium Code.","category":"page"},{"location":"index.html#References","page":"Home","title":"References","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"index.html","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"D. Muir, D. Pfefferlé, Z. Qu, M. Hole, and M. Hegland, ‘Numerical integration of particle orbits in discontinuous fields using VENUS-LEVIS and SPEC’, Computer Physics Communications, p. 108191, Oct. 2021, doi: 10.1016/j.cpc.2021.108191.\nD. Pfefferlé, W. A. Cooper, J. P. Graves, and C. Misev, ‘VENUS-LEVIS and its spline-Fourier interpolation of 3D toroidal magnetic field representation for guiding-centre and full-orbit simulations of charged energetic particles’, Computer Physics Communications, vol. 185, no. 12, pp. 3127–3140, Dec. 2014, doi: 10.1016/j.cpc.2014.08.007.\nS. R. Hudson et al., ‘Computation of multi-region relaxed magnetohydrodynamic equilibria’, Physics of Plasmas, vol. 19, no. 11, p. 112502, Nov. 2012, doi: 10.1063/1.4765691.","category":"page"}]
